Introduction
Attention 
deficit 
hyperactivity 
disorder 
(ADHD) 
is 
a 
neurodevelopmental disorder defined by a persistent pat-
tern of inattention and/or hyperactivity–impulsivity that 
interferes with functioning or development (Diagnostic and 
Statistical Manual Fifth Edition, DSM-5) [1]. ADHD has a world-
wide prevalence rate of about 5.3% [2] and is often associated 
with impairments in everyday life domains, including familial 
relationships, social interactions, and school functioning [3]. 
Psychiatric comorbidities are very common in ADHD, particu-
larly oppositional defiant and conduct disorders, mood and 
anxiety disorders, and substance use disorder [4–6]. Similarly, 
neurodevelopmental disorders, such as specific learning dis-
abilities, developmental coordination disorder, autism spec-
trum disorder, intellectual disability, and tic disorder are also 
common comorbidities [7].
Sleep disorders are also reported as one of the most frequent 
problems in patients with ADHD [8, 9]. Indeed, periodic limb 
movements disorder are reported in approximately 44% of af-
fected people [10, 11], while rates of 25%–55% are reported for 
subjective sleep problems [12], and of 73%–78% for sleep phase 
and circadian sleep–wake rhythm disorders [13, 14]. Sleep-
disordered breathing, a condition ranging from primary snoring 
to more severe disorders like the upper airway resistance syn-
drome, obstructive hypoventilation and obstructive sleep apnea 
(OSA), has been also commonly reported in children with ADHD 
(25%–57%) [15, 16]. Sleep disturbances are so common in ADHD 
that several guidelines recommend a full sleep assessment in 
these patients [17, 18]. However, the ground of these associ-
ations and their possible shared pathophysiological mechan-
isms remain not fully understood [19]. Recent cross-sectional 
studies point to the possible causal role of ADHD-related be-
haviors in affecting sleep hygiene [20], although these behaviors 
would only in part account for the whole clinical picture [19], 
and do not explain the unstable sleep patterns seen in infants at 
high risk for ADHD [21]. On the other hand, sleep disorders may 
themselves foster ADHD-like symptoms, and their treatment, 
for example, the surgical adenotonsillectomy for children with 
OSA, significantly improves ADHD [15, 16]. The complex rela-
tionship between these conditions makes it difficult to establish 
whether sleep problems are comorbidity or, conceivably, a fun-
damental feature of ADHD itself. What is quite clear is that sleep 
problems are causally linked to poorer daytime functioning [22] 
and depressive and oppositional defiant symptoms [23] in ado-
lescents with ADHD. A  vicious circle by which ADHD fosters 
sleep disorders and sleep deprivation worsens ADHD symptoms 
has therefore led to the conceptualization of ADHD as a 24-h 
disorder [24], strongly associated with intra-individual vari-
ability of sleep/wake patterns [25] and clock genes system [26].
Psychostimulants, such as methylphenidate (MPH) and am-
phetamines, and nonpsychostimulant drugs (e.g. atomoxetine 
or guanfacine) are important elements of the multimodal 
therapeutic strategy for ADHD, and are recommended options 
in several guidelines/practice parameters, at least for severe 
cases, or for patients not responding to non-pharmacological 
interventions [27, 28]. Psychostimulants, the first choice medi-
cations for ADHD [27], have been shown to potentially in-
crease the relative risk of insomnia and sleep problems in 
children and adolescents [29], although these adverse effects 
are often transitory (limited to the first weeks of treatment), 
and can often be successfully managed with melatonin [30]. 
This evidence is clinically relevant since psychostimulants 
have great effectiveness in treating ADHD symptoms, with 
one of the highest effect sizes among psychiatric medica-
tions. Moreover, psychostimulants reduce the long term risk 
of physical injuries, substance use disorders and criminal 
act, and improve the academic functioning [28]. The com-
plex overlap between ADHD and sleep disorders has also led 
to further explore the pathophysiological mechanisms shared 
by the two conditions, in order to better elucidate how each 
of them contributes to the pathophysiology of the other [19]. 
Studies focusing on sleep in ADHD, based on sleep diary and 
actigraphy in adolescents, have shown that ADHD is associ-
ated with difficulty falling asleep, shorter night sleep duration, 
greater daytime sleepiness, and more sleep disturbances [31], 
while actigraphy studies on preschoolers showed an increase 
of motor activity during sleep [32]. It has been also proven that 
children with ADHD are objectively sleepier compared with 
typically developing healthy controls (HC) [33, 34]. However, 
actigraphy and polysomnography (PSG)-based studies have re-
vealed only minor findings, namely a small increment of the 
time spent in non-REM (NREM) 1 stage sleep in children with 
ADHD [35], findings not replicated in affected adults [36].
Research evidence also suggests shared neural circuitries 
and neurotransmitter (noradrenergic and dopaminergic) sys-
tems in ADHD [37, 38] and sleep regulation [19] pathophysiology. 
Furthermore, many neuropsychological deficits of ADHD (e.g. 
executive functioning, emotional regulation, learning, working 
memory, impulse control), as well as behavioral manifestations 
(e.g. oppositional and disruptive behaviors) are similarly seen in 
sleep-deprived children [19].
More recent works have therefore looked for alterations in 
microstructural electroencephalographic (EEG) patterns during 
sleep, which have proved to likely represent, in patients with 
ADHD, closer markers of neural plasticity and maturation, cog-
nition and sleep recovery functions [16, 39–51]. However, a clear 
and comprehensive framework of how sleep microstructural 
features affect ADHD domains is still lacking [52] and would 
require an exhaustive assessment of the available evidence, 
including the most recent literature data.
In the present study, we have performed a systematic re-
view and meta-analysis of the literature, specifically focusing 
on the microstructural features of sleep. Indeed, finding out 
reliable EEG microstructure markers of ADHD might provide 
clinicians and researchers with new and likely robust tools 
for dealing with several aspects of the management of ADHD. 
Once assessed as reliable parameters, EEG microstructure fea-
tures might serve to tackle disease risk, early diagnosis, clinical 
characteristics of ADHD and its comorbidities, prognosis and re-
sponse to therapies.

## Key Findings
Discussion
To the best of our knowledge, this is the first meta-analysis per-
formed on microarchitectural sleep findings in ADHD. We sys-
tematically reviewed previous studies focused at assessing the 
microstructure of sleep, namely through spectral and CAP ana-
lyses, in children and adolescents with ADHD compared to non-
ADHD control peers.
We did not find significant differences in spectral power and 
graphoelements between ADHD children and control peers in 
any of the meta-analyzed parameters. Particularly, SWA, SpA, 
and ThA, as well as spindle density, were not significantly dif-
ferent between the two groups. Unfortunately, none of the ana-
lyzed studies had carried out a visual or automatic detection of 
the slow waves, which could have provided possible additional 
parameters of the ultrastructural features (i.e. slope, amplitude, 
duration), potentially serving as further markers of the dis-
ordered sleep in ADHD. To identify potential moderators that 
could have affected ... (Extracted from Discussion)

## Methodology
Methods
Search strategy
We conducted a systematic review of the literature using the 
PRISMA (Preferred Reporting Items for Systematic Reviews and 
Meta-Analyses) guidelines [53] to describe procedures and re-
sults. We searched three bibliographic databases (PubMed, 
Scopus, and Web of Science) from their inception date to May 17, 
2019. To this purpose, we developed a search strategy using the 
following three groups of terms:
