	-	 Group  1: “ADHD” OR “attention deficit hyperactivity dis-
order” OR “hyperkinetic disorder”
	-	 Group 2: “sleep” OR “nap*”
	-	 Group  3: “EEG” OR “electroencephalogr*” OR “PSG” OR 
“polysomnogr*” 
OR “power” 
OR “microstructur*” 
OR 
“architectur*”
Our strategy was to include all relevant titles, abstracts and 
keywords relating to group 1 AND group 2 AND group 3. The 
terms were necessarily adapted for each database and

## Results
results 
were downloaded into Mendeley software. The authors dis-
cussed and reviewed the results of the initial search, which in-
cluded both reviews and original studies. If a previous review 
was found, its reference list was searched to identify and re-
trieve primary studies of interest. We also carefully searched 
reference lists of included original studies to identify relevant 
citations.
Inclusion and exclusion criteria
Studies were retrieved if they met  all the following inclusion 
criteria:
	1.	 Study design: studies aimed at assessing comparable 
microstructural/microarchitectural features of sleep were 
included;
	2.	 Comparison: prospectively diagnosed ADHD patients 
versus non-ADHD control subjects comparison was 
required;
	3.	 Participants: 
only 
children 
and 
adolescents 
aged 
≤18  years were accepted, while no a priori restrictions 
for participants’ gender or intellectual functioning were 
applied;
	4.	 Treatment: no a priori restrictions for previous or cur-
rent ADHD medications were applied; Sleep disorder: no 
a priori restrictions for comorbid sleep disorders were 
applied;
	5.	 EEG recording: no a priori restrictions for EEG techniques 
and procedures were applied; measures: only quantitative 
EEG-based analyses were accepted.
Studies were discarded if they met at least one of the following 
exclusion criteria:
	1.	 ADHD patients versus non-ADHD controls (CTRL) compar-
ison was not performed;
	2.	 ADHD patients were retrospectively diagnosed;
	3.	 The study was performed on overlapping samples with pre-
vious studies;
	4.	 Study participants were adults aged >18 years;
	5.	 The study was aimed at assessing PSG-based macrostruc-
tural features of sleep or non-comparable microstructural/
microarchitectural features of sleep;
	6.	 No quantitative outcomes of sleep EEG assessment were 
available;
	7.	 Sleep was altered by procedures aimed at directly modu-
lating sleep quality during sleep (e.g. transcranial magnetic 
stimulation);
	8.	 The article was written in a language other than English, 
French, Spanish, German, Italian;
	9.	 Reviews, case reports, abstracts, conference posters, and ed-
itorial letters.
Abstract screening and study selection
We retrieved relevant abstracts using our search strategy and 
removed any duplicate. We also identified additional records 
through relevant citations in reference lists of screened pa-
pers and reviews. If a title appeared potentially eligible but no 
abstract was available, the full-text article was retrieved. Two 
researchers (C.B.  and G.S.) scanned all titles and abstracts to 
identify relevant articles for full-text retrieval. Any disagree-
ment was referred to a third researcher (F.S.) and then resolved 
by consensus.
The PRISMA flowchart (Figure 1) shows the process of iden-
tification and selection of papers. Of 1085 abstracts retrieved 
using our search strategy, 491 were removed as duplicates. Four 
additional records were identified through citations in reference 
lists of screened papers and reviews. Thus, 598 (594 + 4) studies 
were screened, of which 560 records were excluded based solely 
on title or abstract. A total of 38 full-text articles were thoroughly 
assessed for eligibility. Among these, 27 articles were excluded, 
and the main reasons for exclusion were the following ones:
	1.	 No ADHD versus CTRL comparison: n = 3;
	2.	 Retrospective ADHD diagnosis: n = 1;
	3.	 Overlapping sample with previous studies: n = 3;
	4.	 Adult participants aged >18 years: n = 1;
	5.	 Macrostructural or noncomparable microstructural assess-
ment: n = 6;
	6.	 Not available quantitative data: n = 4;
	7.	 Sleep quality modulating procedures: n = 1;
	8.	 Other languages: n = 1;
	9.	 Abstracts and posters: n = 7.
Thus, 11 studies were included in the meta-analysis.
Data collection process
For each included study, sample sizes and demographic data 
(age and gender) were extracted from full-text papers, along 
with details on ADHD characteristics (presentation type, se-
verity, diagnostic criteria, and percentage of patients who 
underwent medications for ADHD) and other clinical informa-
tion (intellectual quotient [IQ], comorbid psychiatric conditions 
and associated sleep disorders). Information about sleep record-
ings (EEG procedure, setup and montage) and quantitative EEG 
analyses were carefully obtained.
Summary statistics for each continuous variable were used 
to calculate effect sizes (ES) as outcomes for each study to be 
computed in the subsequent meta-analytic procedure. We chose 
Hedges’ g as a conventionally used and commonly recommended 
measure to calculate ES for each continuous variable of each study, 
since it controls for the potential bias of effect overestimation in 
small studies when compared with other measures [54].
When datasets were not fully available, relevant authors were 
contacted to try and attain the required data, so that all possible 
retrieved studies could be included. If any article failed to pro-
vide means and standard errors (SE) or standard deviations (SD) 
for their continuous outcomes, and authors were uncontactable 
or original data were discarded, lost or irretrievable, ES was esti-
mated from test statistics for their statistical comparisons (e.g. 
p values of independent statistics). Otherwise, SE were imputed 
by calculating the pooled SE from all the other studies included 
in the same meta-analysis, as suggested by Furukawa et al. [55].
