The Cochrane Q test (p-value < 0.05) was employed for hetero-
geneity evaluation, as well as the I2 index (I2 ≤ 50%) was used to 
quantify the heterogeneity of the included studies. If the studies 
were found to be statistically homogeneous, then the fixed-
effects model was used to compute Hedges’ g as summary ES 
measure with a 95% confidence interval (CI) and to pool data. 
Otherwise, a random-effects model was conducted. The Der 
Simonian and Laird estimator was used to calculate the pooled 
ES and assess its statistical significance. A p-value < 0.05 was 
considered statistically significant. All statistical analyses were 
performed using RStudio software.
Meta-regressions
Univariate meta-regressions were performed when possible (at 
least four studies available for the parameters under consideration) 
to identify potential moderators that could affect non-significant 
differences in meta-analyses. Well-known patient-related vari-
ables associated with variable levels of SWA were therefore evalu-
ated by meta-regression including weighted mean age of patients 
and controls, gender (% male) and percentage of patients exposed 
to ADHD current or past medications as predictors of the models. 
All meta-regressions were performed using the mixed-effect 
model and weighted by the inverse variance of each study.
Results
For the 11 included studies, we report a narrative synthesis of 
the findings in terms of clinical and demographic characteris-
tics of selected samples, EEG recording procedures and sleep 
microstructure analysis results (Tables 1 and 2). The most recent 
terminology of sleep was used whenever possible, according to 
American Academy of Sleep Medicine guidelines [56]; however, 
since publication dates of included studies ranged from 1987 to 
2019, this condition could understandably not be always applied.
Spectral power analysis and graphoelements
Six studies performed a spectral analysis of EEG power during 
sleep in the main frequency bands. Spectral analysis data pre-
sented here for each frequency band refer to recordings at elec-
trodes C3/C4 or F4, which demonstrated similar findings in a 
previous study [57], or refer to the average power of multiple 
high-density EEG channels.
Forrest plots of the four meta-analyses of EEG power and 
graphoelements are displayed in Figure  2. The meta-analyses 
evaluated three parameters of spectral power analysis (SWA, 
SpA, and ThA) and one parameter of ultrastructural ana-
lysis (SpD). Each meta-analysis included a variable number of 
studies ranging from two to six [39, 41, 43, 46, 47, 51, 58, 59]. 
Heterogeneity of the studies varied considerably among the ex-
plored parameters, with I2 index ranging from 0% to 80.5% and 
Cochrane Q test p-values ranging from 0.451 to 0.024. Thus, ei-
ther fixed- or random-effects model was applied accordingly, as 
clarified in the Methods section. No meta-analyses showed sig-
nificant results.
On univariate meta-regressions (see Figure 3 and 4), the dif-
ferential SWA between ADHD patients and HC was negatively 
associated with both mean age (β = –0.178, SE = 0.067, p = 0.008) 
and the use of ADHD medications in the study populations 
under consideration (β = –0.009, SE = 0.003, p = 0.014), each model 
individually explaining the greatest amount of the variability in 
the effects size data (respectively, R2
age = 100%, R2
medications = 100%), 
while no significance was found for gender (p = 0.687). No meta-
regressions were performed on SpA and ThA due to the rela-
tive paucity of available studies, respectively three (SpA) and 
two (ThA).
CAP analysis
In three of the included studies, CAP analysis was performed 
according to standard criteria [60]. Forrest plots of the twenty-
three meta-analyses of CAP parameters are displayed in Figure 5. 
The meta-analyses evaluated 23 sleep variables of CAP micro-
structure analysis and included the three above-mentioned 
studies [42, 45, 61]. Heterogeneity of the studies varied con-
siderably among the explored parameters, with I2 index ran-
ging from 0% to 85.36% and Cochrane Q test p-values ranging 
from 0.983 to 0.001. Thus, either fixed or random effects model 
was applied accordingly, as clarified in the Methods section. 
Only three meta-analyses showed significant results: total 
CAP rate in NREM2 sleep was significantly lower in ADHD pa-
tients than controls (standard mean difference [SMD] = –0.963, 
95% CI  =  [–1.733; –0.193], p  =  0.014, I2  =  71%, Q-test p  =  0.032) 
(Figure 6A); CAP A1 rate in NREM sleep was significantly lower 
in ADHD patients than controls (SMD = –0.691, 95% CI = [–1.087; 
–0.295], p < 0.001, I2 = 0%, Q-test p = 0.403) (Figure 6B); CAP A1 
index in NREM2 sleep was significantly lower in ADHD patients 
than controls (SMD = –1.152, 95% CI = [–2.276; –0.029], p = 0.044, 
I2 = 85%, Q-test p = 0.001) (Figure 6C). Unfortunately, since only 
three studies performed CAP analysis, no further subgroup or 
meta-regression analysis was conducted to identify the relevant 
source of variability in the results of single studies.

## Clinical Significance
conclusions
Before concluding, we need specifying some limitations of the 
study that could be useful to reliably interpret these results. 
First, we have arbitrarily assumed that SWA evaluated either 
on C3/C4, or on F4, or through the average power of multiple 
high-density EEG channels could be compared. This assumption 
was necessary to perform a meta-analysis of the available data, 
in order to deal with the heterogeneity of the methods among 
studies. Secondly, we accepted mild differences in the frequency 
bands considered for classifying SWA, SpA, and ThA (as reported 
in Table 1) because row data were not available, in the attempt to 
establish more standardized intervals. However, meta-analyses 
were conducted on estimated effect sizes so that the relative 
differences between ADHD patients and HC were the only sum-
mary measures, and this has allowed us to reduce the impact of 
the previously mentioned limitation. A third limitation is that 
samples were not homogeneous in terms of clinical details, 
with studies including either pre-medicated or medicated or 
drug-naïve patients, with different age ranges, and one study 
including ADHD patients with comorbid sleep disorders and 
psychopathologies. Heterogeneity was considered in the meta-
analysis process and either fixed or random effects models were 
accordingly applied. However, we could not provide a quality 
rating of the included papers since an appropriate tool that 
could be purposefully applied to assess the quality of the studies 
included in our review is lacking.
That said, we conclude that SWA and CAP A1 are potential 
highly reliable markers of differences in sleep microarchitecture 
in ADHD. As such, they can help to evaluate alterations in cor-
tical maturation reflecting the neuropsychological and behav-
ioral deficits of the disorder. On the other hand, only a few 
studies focusing on the role of sleep spindles and REM theta 
activity in ADHD, as well as on SWA and CAP topography, were 
available, especially in children. Further research will hope-
fully fill these gaps, especially if based on shared standardized 
protocols for sleep evaluation and EEG markers detection, and 
Downloaded from https://academic.oup.com/sleep/advance-article/doi/10.1093/sleep/zsab006/6081934 by University of Cambridge user on 28 May 2021
12  |  SLEEPJ, 2021, Vol. XX, No. XX
comparable age groups. These future studies, including and 
comparing treated and untreated ADHD patients with different 
age ranges, will probably be even more valuable if based on a 
dimensional approach to the disorder, namely evaluating the 
symptoms and neuropsychological deficits of ADHD as lying on 
a continuum from common traits present in healthy individuals 
to the clinically relevant condition [96]. Reliable and specific EEG 
markers of individual ADHD dimensions could grant better pre-
vention through early detection of at-risk or milder clinical con-
ditions, better tailored therapeutic interventions, and prediction 
of treatment response.
